	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540469_01.jpg"/>
			<p>Autobiography from the Time of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">German
					Occupation</term></p>
			<p>When the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> broke out in <date when="1939"
					>1939</date>, I was in the city of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093133/lodz.html">Łódź</placeName> (<placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName>). In the ninth month [<date when="1939-09"
					>September</date>] the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> entered <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093133/lodz.html">Łódź</placeName>. The day that the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>Germans</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1101" type="subject">entered</term> the city it became a hell.
				Immediately, on the first day, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-951" type="subject">decrees</term> were
				issued stating that the Jews <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-339" type="subject">must not walk</term>
				down the main streets and Jewish businesses must <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject"
					>display a label</term> with a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">yellow Star of
					David</term>. Then they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-636" type="subject">seized</term> [<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term>] for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term> from every house and they gave Jews the
				hardest work. Then they again made a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-951" type="subject">decree</term>
				that Jews must wear <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">yellow patches</term>; this
				allowed <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> to identify who is a Jew and
				then <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-642" type="subject">they beat us</term> terribly on the streets so
				that indeed no one could go out in the street. Thus my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822"
					type="subject">family</term> decided to leave <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093133/lodz.html">Łódź</placeName>. After
				four months we all left <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093133/lodz.html">Łódź</placeName>, because they made a terrible
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>, for <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7532988/polaniec.html">Połaniec</placeName> (<placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/769250/kielce.html">Kielce</placeName> region, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName>), my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">grandmother</term> lived there in the shtetl and we
				all lived with her. We began a new life there. It was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">better</term> for us than in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093133/lodz.html">Łódź</placeName>. My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> began to trade and made a living. And so
				two years passed; not so calmly, there were various <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject"
					>deportations</term> in a small format. <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-429">SS</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term> fell upon the shtetl and constantly took
				a few <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term>. Once we heard in the shtetl
				the news that the entire shtetl was to be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-551" type="subject"
					>liquidated</term>. My <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> decided to give me to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term> and they would pay her. Once, in the
				ninth month of <date when="1942-09">1942</date>, when my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822"
					type="subject">family</term> was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hidden</term>
				in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term></p>
			<p><pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540469_02.jpg"/></p>
			<p>made especially as a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">hiding place</term>, which my
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> had built—I knew the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">hiding place</term> but I did not know how it
				looked—one morning a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer woman</term> came to us.
				My <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">dressed</term> me nicely and did not give me any
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, only money, because the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer woman</term> was to look after me in return for
				money. You cannot imagine how the parting from my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>parents</term> was, I will never forget it my entire life. Above all, I cannot write it down. With sadness I had to leave my
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">parents</term>, but then something happened and,
				with God’s help, I met my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">family</term> again. I
				left home with the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer woman</term> and we needed
				to go to the village there where this <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer
					woman</term> lived. When we had already gone three kilometers and were in a forest, she said that she needed to take care of
				something and must go away for ten minutes. And so I waited for her and waited for half an hour, I saw that she was not coming back
				and I understood that she had taken the money and would not return. She <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-191" type="subject">had made a run</term> for it. It was already nighttime
				when I came out of the forest and found myself standing in a field where <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">shepherds</term> were herding their animals and taking
				them home. They did not identify me as a Jew when I went up to them, and I asked them where is the way to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7532988/polaniec.html">Połaniec</placeName>, and they showed me the right way. Then I found the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term> where my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">parents</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">family</term> were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hiding</term>. I</p>
			<p><pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540469_03.jpg"/></p>
			<p>called out, <q><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">Mother</term></q>, because I did not
				know where the entrance was to get inside the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject"
					>bunker</term>. They were very shocked to see me and I too was surprised seeing the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term> where we would have to live for we did
				not know how long. This was in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">stable</term>,
				under the hay and under the earth. It was a pit lined with boards: its height maybe be one meter and its breadth three meters. On the
				floor was spread out bedding and we had to lie on the bedding because it was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">impossible to stand up</term>. The owner of the stable
				took payment of 4500 zlotys per month. At night my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>father</term> went out from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term>
				to bring the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">water</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> which the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer</term> prepared in advance, and so it was from
				the beginning of our life in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term>.
				However, after a while the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer</term> said that
				he could not risk buying <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> for us anymore,
				and from that time onwards began for us the worst and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">bitterest time</term> of life and as a result of this my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">killed</term>. The supply of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> ran out and we were left without hope. My
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> went out every night to get <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. However, he now did not bring <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> but only raw <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">cabbage</term> leaves, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">onions</term>, and so we lived from this the entire
				year of <date when="1943">1943</date> and the first half of <date when="1944">1944</date>. My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> suffered very much with her stomach and
				it pained her very much and she was very <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject"
				>sick</term>. My little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term></p>
			<p><pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540469_04.jpg"/></p>
			<p>somehow hung on, as did I. My <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> said
				nothing but it was clear from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">Father</term>’s face
				that he suffered very much from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">hunger</term> and
				also morally: it pained him greatly that he could not help us and he did his best to help us. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">hunger</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">cold</term> made us very dispirited and we saw no end
				to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term>. Once, on <date when="1944-06-25"
					>June 25, 1944</date>, my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> went out
				from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term> at night thinking that he
				would go to another village five kilometers way and there he would buy <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, because my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> could no longer eat the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">cabbage</term> leaves. He went and did not come back.
				I cried the whole night. My <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> began to
				feel much worse and we had no news about my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>father</term>. So I said to my little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>brother</term> that he should go and find out what had happened to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term>. My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term> went out and came back and told us he
				heard that our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> had been caught by the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmers</term>; what they did with him I do not
				know to this day. We cried day and night but <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>father</term> did not come back. However, our luck had already evaporated, as bread always falls on the buttered side. After two
				months the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer</term> who owned the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term> came to us and spoke to us in this way:
					<q>The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_russians">Russians</term> have torn through the front and the <term
						ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> are fleeing and searching all homes and fields. Therefore I am afraid to
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hide</term> you anymore.</q> And he told us
				that we should give him money and he would take us into a deep forest where</p>
			<p><pb n="5" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540469_05.jpg"/></p>
			<p>we could <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hide</term> ourselves and he would help us.
				And we listened to him and we had no other counsel. So the next day, in the morning when it was still very dark, he rode up to the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term> in a wagon and we came out from
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">hidden bunker</term>. Going out from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">bunker</term> we could not stand on our feet and all
				three of us went onto the wagon. Together with my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>brother</term> I carried my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> to
				the wagon, because she was very weak, and we drove off. After half an hour of travelling we reached some water. The wagon stopped and
				he told us to get off the wagon. By the water stood the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-195"
					type="subject">farmer’s brother</term>. And then began a terrible scene which I will never in my life forget. He quickly pulled
				her [my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term>] down murderously and threw
				her into the water, and he beat me severely, and then my little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822"
					type="subject">brother</term>. But in the blink of an eye I tore myself from his hands and sprang into the water. I began walking
				in the water to the other side. It became dark and I did not have strength to go on. With my last strength I barely managed to run
				across. I went on without stopping for 5–6 kilometers. I saw the other village. There I went up to the first, best <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer</term>, banged on the door and went in and
				begged the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer woman</term> that was there
				inside, telling her that I was from the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/690791/ukraine.html">Ukraine</placeName> and when the
					<term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_russians">Russians</term> invaded I fled.</p>
			<p><pb n="6" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540469_06.jpg"/></p>
			<p>I asked that she should take me in to tend to the livestock. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825"
					type="subject">woman</term> had mercy on me and she took me in and I <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> there for a long time and it was good
				for me. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term> treated me well, like her
				own <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term>. But one day the same <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-195" type="subject">farmer</term> who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term> my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> and little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term>, he must have found out that I was
				there, and he told the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer woman</term> that I
				was a Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1000" type="subject">communist</term> and she must not keep me. When he
				said this to her in one room, I heard it all from another room. Hearing this, I was very frightened that she would hand me in and I
				fled through the other door. I fled without even stopping to breathe, until I came to another village. And there I went to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">farmer woman</term>. I <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> very hard and did not have enough to
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term>. But I was not there for long and
				finally the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_russians">Russians</term> came to the village and I was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term>. But sadly alone. The day of
				happiness was <date when="1944-08-02">August 2, 1944</date>. After spending a few weeks in the village I saw how the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-536"
					type="subject">killing Jews</term> after the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject"
					>liberation</term>. I travelled to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3100946/czestochowa.html">Częstochowa</placeName>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_pinczewska_rozia">Pinczewska Rozia</persName> geb. <date when="1931-12-10">10/12 1931</date></p>
			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3093133/lodz.html">Lodz</placeName> (<placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poiln</placeName>)</p>
			<p>Je[t]zt Kibuc Nocham [<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp">Bergen Belsen</placeName>]</p>
